Beginning

Beginning with a community of 1000 energy units divided into two species of fairly different sizes. The two species have equal shares of the energy. This means there are more individuals of the smaller species.

E is stable

Stable E, N decreases

First achieved by increasing the average size and therefore metabolic rate.

The average m of an individual increases more than the average e of an individual, because \(e \propto m ^ .75\).

The total M increases, again because of the .75 scaling.

I think but am not confident hat this must always happen with M. If average e increases with stable E, I think you must be shifting to larger engines on average, meaning you get more biomass and a larger M, m.

What happens if we use the same changes to N and E but drastically change the size structure?

E is stable, N increases

Achieved by decreasing the average size.

Average metabolic rate decreases.

Average individual size decreases, more than the average metabolic rate.

Total biomass decreases. Generally, if a community is shifting to smaller species, you will lose biomass faster than you lose energy use.

##                 variable     ratio
## 1                E ratio 0.9992553
## 2                N ratio 1.1944444

## 5        avg size change 0.7794707
## 6 size change / e change 0.9317283

E increases

E increases and N increases proportionally

Here we have increased E by 1.5 by amplifying the original community without changing the underlying size structure.
